# Backend (Java / Spring Boot / Spring Modulith)

## Module structure

- A new module = a new folder under `backend/modules/<name>/`. Do not edit
  `settings.gradle.kts` — it discovers modules automatically by scanning that
  directory. If a module isn't showing up, the folder is in the wrong place,
  not a settings problem.
- Module `build.gradle.kts` should normally be exactly:
```kotlin
  plugins {
      id("quickapp.module-conventions")
  }
```
  If a module needs an extra dependency beyond what the convention plugin gives
  it (Java 25 toolchain, Spring Boot BOM, spring-context, JUnit 5 test wiring),
  add it directly to that module's `build.gradle.kts`. Do not modify the shared
  convention plugin for a one-module need.
- Anything implementing module logic that shouldn't be visible to other modules
  goes in an `internal` sub-package. Anything another module (or `backend`
  itself) is meant to call goes in the module's top-level package.
- Cross-module communication: Spring application events, not direct calls into
  another module's `internal` package. If you find yourself wanting to import
  from another module's `internal`, that's a signal the interaction should be
  an event, or the shared piece should be pulled into its own module.

## Verifying module boundaries

- `backend/src/test/.../ModularityTests.java` calls `ApplicationModules.verify()`.
  Run it after any change that touches module structure:
./gradlew :backend:test --tests ModularityTests
- This must pass before a backend PR merges. A failure here means a boundary
  was actually violated — fix the structure, don't weaken the test.

## New endpoint checklist

- Controller + DTO in the module's public package (not `internal`).
- Business logic in `internal`.
- Update `contracts/openapi.yaml` for the new/changed endpoint.
- Unit test for the logic, integration test (Testcontainers, real Postgres) for
  the endpoint itself.
- Use constructor injection, not field injection.

## Known Gradle/Spring gotchas (hit and fixed once already — don't rediscover these)

- Any module whose main code uses a Spring annotation (`@Service`, `@Component`,
  `@Repository`, etc.) needs Spring on its classpath. The convention plugin
  already provides this — but if you're ever writing a module's build file by
  hand instead of applying the convention, remember: `spring-context` as an
  `implementation` dependency, plus the Spring Boot BOM via
  `dependencyManagement { imports { mavenBom(...) } }`. Without the BOM, you'd
  have to pin a version number by hand and it can drift from the rest of the app.
- `useJUnitPlatform()` must be set on the `test` task, or Gradle silently looks
  for JUnit 4-style tests and reports "no tests found" even when JUnit 5 tests
  exist and compile fine. Already set in the convention plugin.
- Repositories (`mavenCentral()`) are declared once, centrally, in
  `dependencyResolutionManagement` inside the root `settings.gradle.kts` — not
  per-module. A module with no repository access will fail to resolve any
  dependency with a "no repositories are defined" error.
- Precompiled script plugins (files like `quickapp.module-conventions.gradle.kts`
  inside `build-logic`) cannot use the generated `libs.x.y` version-catalog
  shortcut — Gradle doesn't guarantee those accessors work inside a file that's
  itself defining a plugin. Use
  `extensions.getByType<VersionCatalogsExtension>().named("libs")` and
  `.findLibrary(...)` / `.findVersion(...)` instead.

## Running tests
./gradlew :backend:test                    # all backend unit tests
./gradlew :backend:test --tests <ClassName> # one test class
Report the actual pass/fail result — don't assume a test passed without running it.